Question 1.2 - (10 pts) Create a function called z_score_standardization in which you should define the logic to perform z-score standardization. In a new R chunk, standardize the explanatory variables using the aforementioned function.

z_score_standardization <- function(x) {
  (x - mean(x)) / sd(x)
}
forest_fires_norm <- forest_fires %>% 
  
  ## remove categorical data since only numeric 
  ## values are valid for euclidean distance calculation
  select(-one_of("month", "day")) %>%
  ## min-max normalization for all columns except area
  mutate_at(c(1:ncol(.)-1), z_score_standardization) %>% 
  ## log transform non-zero area values because area 
  ## is skewed towards 0
  mutate(area =  log(area + 1))

Question 1.3 - (50 pts) Implement the k-NN algorithm in R (do not use an implementation of k-NN from a package). Create a function with the following name and arguments: kNN-regression(data_train, label_train, data_test, k); data_train represents the explanatory variables from the training set and label_trainrepresents the corresponding response variable for each observation in data_train i.e.Â it will contain the burned area of the forest. The data_test represents the observations from the test set and k is the selected value of k (i.e.Â the number of neighbors.)

Create functions:

## (euclidean) distance function
dis_fn <- function(a, b) {
  d <- 0
  for (i in 1:length(a)) {
    d <- d + (a[i] - b[i])^2
  }
  return(sqrt(d))
}

## regression function
kNN_regression <- function(k, data_train, label_train, data_test) {
  
  ## convert train and test data rows to lapply-frienldly list elements
  train_list <- 
    data_train %>% 
    split(seq(nrow(.)))
  
  test_list <- 
    data_test %>% 
    split(seq(nrow(.)))
  
  ## apply function to each test data row
  lapply(test_list,
         function(x){
           ## the first output are the label (area) values of k neighbors
           labs <- label_train %>% slice(c(
             train_list %>%
               ## apply the distance function to each test row
               lapply(dis_fn, x) %>%
               ## order the output and pull the top k values
               unlist(use.names = FALSE) %>% order() %>% head(k))) %>% 
             pull()
           ## get the median value for k nearest neighbors
           labs %>% median()
         }) %>% unlist(use.names = FALSE)
}

Question 1.5 - (15 pts) Provide all values between 3 and 33 inclusive as the value of k (you can increment k by 2).

(5 pts) Create a line chart and plot each value of k (from the previous step) on the x-axis and the corresponding MSE on the y-axis. Explain the chart and determine which value of k is more suitable and why.

Very long-running block (75 minutes)

knn_mse <-
  lapply(seq(3, 33, 2),                   ## run the regression algorithm
       kNN_regression,                    ## for k = 3 - 33 with increments of 2
       data_train   = fires_train_data,
       label_train  = fires_train_labels, 
       data_test    = fires_test_data) %>%
  lapply(function(x) {                    
    cbind(x,                              ## create a table with the test data
          fires_test_data,                ## for each value of k
          fires_test_labels) %>%
      tibble() %>%
      mutate(error = area - x) %>%        ## calculate the error for each table
  summarise(
    mse = sum(error^2 / length(error)))
  }) %>% unlist() %>% tibble() %>%        ## create a new table of calculated errors
  rename("mse" = ".") %>% 
  mutate(k = seq(3, 33, 2))

How does the MSE change if k-NN is determined using the mode instead of median?
We can modify the k-NN function to check:

kNN_regression <- function(k, data_train, label_train, data_test) {
  train_list <- 
    data_train %>% 
    split(seq(nrow(.)))
  
  test_list <- 
    data_test %>% 
    split(seq(nrow(.)))
  
  lapply(test_list,
         function(x){
           labs <- label_train %>% slice(c(
             train_list %>%
               lapply(dis_fn, x) %>%
               unlist(use.names = FALSE) %>% order() %>% head(k))) %>% 
             pull()
           ## determine the mode without using additional packages
           ## (for fun)
           labs[lapply(unique(labs),
                       function(x) { which(x == labs) }) %>%
                  lapply(length) %>% unlist() %>% max()]
         }) %>% unlist(use.names = FALSE)
}

What about using the mean k-NN value? (75-minute run)

kNN_regression <- function(k, data_train, label_train, data_test) {
  train_list <- 
    data_train %>% 
    split(seq(nrow(.)))
  
  test_list <- 
    data_test %>% 
    split(seq(nrow(.)))
  
  ## apply function to each test data row
  lapply(test_list,
         function(x){
           ## the first output are the label (area) values of k neighbors
           labs <- label_train %>% slice(c(
             train_list %>%
               ## apply the distance function to each test row
               lapply(dis_fn, x) %>%
               ## order the output and pull the top k values
               unlist(use.names = FALSE) %>% order() %>% head(k))) %>% 
             pull()
           ## get the median value for k nearest neighbors
           labs %>% mean()
         }) %>% unlist(use.names = FALSE)
}
